Hello, this is 6 Minute English from BBC Learning English. I'm Neil

3
00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:21.000
And I'm Beth. Women today are having fewer babies. More women are delaying having children until their 40s.

4
00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:26.000
10 years in life between 40 and 49.

5
00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:32.000
And some women are giving birth in their 50s, their 60s, even their 70s.

6
00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:39.000
There are many reasons behind the trend for older moms, including better access to education and careers.

7
00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:45.000
But there are also health risks to having children later in life. So in this program, we'll be asking

8
00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:52.000
when are you two old to have a baby. And as usual, we'll be learning some useful new vocabulary as well.

9
00:00:52.000 --> 00:01:03.000
But first, I have a question for you, Neil. In 2019, Mangi Yamayera-Mati gave birth to twins in the state of Andro-Prodesh, South India.

10
00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:11.000
But these were no ordinary twins because Mangi Yamma was the oldest recorded woman ever to give birth.

11
00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:20.000
So, how old was the oldest ever mum when she gave birth? Was she a 53 years old?

12
00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:26.000
B 63 years old? Or C 73 years old?

13
00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:29.000
I'm going to guess 63.

14
00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:34.000
OK, Neil, we'll find out the correct answer at the end of the program.

15
00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:44.000
Professor of reproductive science at University College London, Dr. Harper, has been studying the trend of women choosing to have babies later in life.

16
00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:50.000
Here, she shares her discoveries with BBC World Service program, global story.

17
00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:59.000
10, 20, 30 years ago, women were having children at a much younger age. Now it's become quite normal for women in their 30s.

18
00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:05.000
As we see with the world data, there's many countries where women have their first birth over the age of 30.

19
00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:12.000
But this is quite a new phenomena. That's why this term geriatric mother unfortunately still lingers.

20
00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:18.000
Professor Harper uses the word phenomena to describe the trend for older mothers.

21
00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:30.000
For nominers are unusual or significant facts and events that exist and are talked about. People often get this wrong, but the plural form is phenomena and the singular is phenomenon.

22
00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:37.000
The concept of older mothers is still quite a new phenomenon, and attitudes towards them are changing.

23
00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:43.000
Mothers over the age of 35 used to be called geriatric, a word many found offensive.

24
00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:49.000
Fortunately, this term is no longer used, but social disapproval of older mothers still lingers.

25
00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:54.000
If something lingers, it continues to exist longer than usual or expected.

26
00:02:54.000 --> 00:03:05.000
Yes, in some cultures, older mothers are still disapproved of. But wait a minute, Neil, it takes two to make a baby. What's the man's role in all of this?

27
00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:13.000
Well, unlike women, whose ability to naturally get pregnant declines sharply in their 40s, men's fertility lasts longer.

28
00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:21.000
Rolling Stone singer Mick Jagger famously had his eighth child with his 29-year-old partner at the age of 73.

29
00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:26.000
So, are older fathers more socially acceptable than older mothers?

30
00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:32.000
Yes, things Professor Harper, as she explained to BBC World Services Global Story.

31
00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:42.000
Do you have a bit of a gender problem? Because if this was a man in his 60s, 70s and even 80s, and he's father to child, most people would pass him on the back.

32
00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:48.000
But they probably pass him on the back because he's absolutely got so much younger partner.

33
00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:59.000
But if we've got a woman in her 60s, 70s or got a bit 80s having a child, then it does have a sort of shock reaction and makes people feel uncomfortable.

34
00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:05.000
Professor Harper thinks that society is more accepting of older fathers than older mothers.

35
00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:15.000
A 70-year-old man can still father a child. He can make a woman pregnant who then gives birth, and most people would pat him on the back.

36
00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:19.000
An idiom meaning gives someone praise or congratulations.

37
00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:25.000
On the other hand, says Professor Harper, God forbid a woman having a baby in her 80s.

38
00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:31.000
Here the phrase God forbid is used as a way of saying you hope something will not happen.

39
00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:43.000
There's another side to this story, though. In the West, young women from Gen Z, the generation born since the year 2000, are saying they won't have children at all.

40
00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:51.000
In more traditional countries, meanwhile, a woman's role is as a mother, and many pray to God to be blessed with a child.

41
00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:59.000
Which is exactly what happens to Mangi Yamayaramati. The South Indian woman I asked you about in my question, Neil.

42
00:04:59.000 --> 00:05:05.000
In 2019, she became the oldest recorded woman ever to give birth.

43
00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:09.000
And I guess she was 63 years old at the time.

44
00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:17.000
Which was the wrong answer I'm afraid. In fact, she was even older. 73.

45
00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:23.000
Okay, let's recap the vocabulary we've learnt in this program, starting with the phrase, In Your 40s.

46
00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:29.000
Which describes the period of 10 years in some months life when they're aged between 40 and 49.

47
00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:37.000
Phenomenar describes any significant facts or events that we know exist and can be observed and discussed.

48
00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:43.000
If something lingers, it continues to exist longer than usual or expected.

49
00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:49.000
The verb to father means to make a woman pregnant who then gives birth to a child.

50
00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:55.000
The idiom, Pat someone on the back, is used to describe giving someone praise, congratulations, or encouragement.

51
00:05:55.000 --> 00:06:01.000
And finally, the expression God forbid is a way of saying that you hope something will not happen.

52
